<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-05-04T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-05-04T13:00:00-05:00" n="897" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d897">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.6363 Manchuria/198: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-05-04T14:00:00-04:00">May 4, 1935—2
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>75. Your 94, May 2, 5 p.m.<note n="5" xml:id="d897fn5">Not
                                printed.</note> For your information. According to Standard-Vacuum,
                            New York office of Asiatic Petroleum received from London on May 2 a
                            telegram to the effect that it has also been decided in London that the
                            Asiatic Petroleum should in the first place apply only to Manchuria and
                            should not approach Tokyo unless it later becomes necessary to make a
                            claim.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>